          <p>
            <b>OSINT stands for Open Source Intelligence.</b> It refers to the process of collecting and analysing information from publicly available sources such as social media, websites, news articles, and other open sources. OSINT is often used in intelligence, law enforcement, and corporate investigations to gather information on individuals, organisations, or events.
          </p>
          <p>
            <i>"OSINT is not just a collection of information, but a process of analyzing and synthesizing information from multiple sources to create actionable intelligence." - Robert David Steele, former CIA officer and author of "The Open-Source Everything Manifesto"</i>
          </p>
          <img src="/images/banner.jpeg" class="large-centre-img"alt="OSINT">
          <p>
            OSINT can be used to identify potential threats, monitor competitors, investigate crimes, and support decision-making processes. It involves searching for information, analysing and validating the data, and then presenting the findings in a useful format.
          </p>
          <p>
            There are many tools and techniques that can be used for OSINT, including search engines, social media monitoring tools, and data analysis software. It is important to use ethical and legal methods when conducting OSINT, as accessing certain types of information or violating privacy laws can result in legal consequences.
          </p>
